</blockquote>

<p><a href="https://twitter.com/gdb/status/1725736242137182594">According to Brockman</a>â€‰â€”â€‰who until he quit in protest of Altmanâ€™s firing was chairman of the OpenAI boardâ€‰â€”â€‰he didnâ€™t find out until just 5 minutes before Altman was sacked. Iâ€™ve never once heard of a corporate board firing the companyâ€™s CEO behind the back of the chairman of the board.</p>

<p>It really does look more and more like a deep philosophical fissure inside OpenAI, between those led by Sutskever (and, obviously, a majority of the board) advocating a cautious slow and genuinely non-profit-driven approach, and Altman/Brockmanâ€™s â€œletâ€™s move fast, change the world, and make a lot of moneyâ€ side. Sutskever and the OpenAI board seemingly see Altman/Brockman as reckless swashbucklers; Altman and Brockman, I suspect, see Sutskever and his side as a bunch of ninnies.</p>

<p>A simple way to look at it is to read <a href="https://openai.com/charter">OpenAIâ€™s charter</a>, â€œthe principles we use to execute on OpenAIâ€™s missionâ€. Itâ€™s a mere 423 words, and very plainly written. It doesnâ€™t sound anything at all like the company Altman has been running. The board, it appears, believes in the charter. How in the world it took them until now to realize Altman was leading OpenAI in directions completely contrary to their charter is beyond me.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s like <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SjbPi00k_ME">the police chief in <em>Casablanca</em> being â€œshockedâ€‰â€”â€‰shocked!â€</a> to find out that gambling was taking place in a casino <em>where he played</em>.&nbsp;<a class="permalink" title="Permanent link to â€˜More on Sam Altmanâ€™s Ouster From OpenAIâ€™" href="https://daringfireball.net/2023/11/more_altman_openai">&#9733;</a></p>

