<h2 class="dateline">Thursday, 16 November 2023</h2>
<dl class="linkedlist">
<dt>
<a href="https://www.techradar.com/phones/iphone/breaking-apple-will-support-rcs-in-2024">Apple Announces Intention to Support RCS Messages â€˜Next Yearâ€™</a>&nbsp;<a class="permalink" title="Permanent link to â€˜Apple Announces Intention to Support RCS Messages â€˜Next Yearâ€™â€™" href="https://daringfireball.net/linked/2023/11/16/apple-rcs">&#9733;</a>
</dt>
<dd>
<p>Lance Ulanoff, reporting for TechRadar:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>RCS or Rich Communication Services, a communications standard 
developed by the GSM Association and adopted by much of the 
Android ecosystem, is designed to universally elevate messaging 
communication across mobile devices. Even though Apple has been 
working with the group, it has until this moment steadfastly 
refused to add RCS support to iPhones. Now, however, Apple is 
changing its tune. </p>

<p>â€œLater next year, we will be adding support for RCS Universal 
Profile, the standard as currently published by the GSM 
Association. We believe the RCS Universal Profile will offer a 
better interoperability experience when compared to SMS or MMS. 
This will work alongside iMessage, which will continue to be the 
best and most secure messaging experience for Apple users,â€ said 
an Apple spokesperson. [...] </p>

<p>When RCS does arrive on your best iPhone, though, it means the end 
of the â€œgreen bubble shameâ€ for your best Android phone-owning 
friends, family, and coworkers. Theyâ€™ll be able to send and 
receive high-resolution photos and videos from their phones to 
your iPhone. Group messaging could become platform agnostic. And 
theyâ€™ll be able to share their location with you through 
RCS-supported messaging. </p>

<p>There is, naturally, a wrinkle here. The RCS standard still 
doesnâ€™t support end-to-end encryption. Apple, which has offered 
encrypted messaging for over a decade, is kind of a stickler about 
security. Apple says it wonâ€™t be supporting any proprietary 
extensions that seek to add encryption on top of RCS and hopes, 
instead, to work with the GSM Association to add encryption to the 
standard. </p>
</blockquote>

<p>Color me surprised by Appleâ€™s change of heart here. Also color me utterly <em>un</em>surprised that Apple has no intention to support Googleâ€™s proprietary extensions to RCS that allow for E2EE. Itâ€™s a disgrace, in my opinion, that E2EE wasnâ€™t a foundational part of the RCS spec from the start, but if Apple is going to support RCS, they should support RCS by-the-spec, not Googleâ€™s proprietary version.</p>

<p>I suspect that in practical terms, this might have almost no discernible effect on the user experience. RCS messages are not going to be blueâ€‰â€”â€‰<s>theyâ€™re either going to stay green, just like SMS/MMS messages, or perhaps Apple will add a new color (purple?) for RCS</s>. I suspect RCS messages will just remain green though, and itâ€™ll be treated as what it is: the next generation of phone-carrier-based messaging. I think any initial coverage today framing this as the end of the green/blue disparity is totally wrong. Itâ€™s just about making green messages higher quality and more reliable. <strong>Update:</strong> I confirmed with Apple today that RCS messages will be green, just like SMS and MMS messages.</p>

<p>The best part of the experience, for users, is that RCS supports higher-resolution photos and videos. The worst part is that itâ€™s not encrypted, and Apple caving and deciding to support it will expand, rather than contract, the amount of messaging that is not E2EE. And whatâ€™s the plan for when (if?) E2EE gets added to the official RCS spec? Will Apple then <em>drop</em> support for non-encrypted RCS messages? Or add some sort of indicatorâ€‰â€”â€‰a badge or different message colorâ€‰â€”â€‰to indicate which messages are truly encrypted and which are not?</p>

<p>There were also reports from just last year that RCS was being abused to send large amounts of spam in Indiaâ€‰â€”â€‰see reports here from <a href="https://www.theverge.com/2022/5/18/23121150/google-messages-india-rcs-ads">The Verge</a> and <a href="https://9to5google.com/2022/05/17/google-messages-rcs-ads-india/">9to5Google</a>.</p>

</dd>


